  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering through several key mechanisms and frameworks:\n\n1. International Standards and Conventions\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Provide standardized approaches to combating money laundering\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance Treaties (MLATs)\n- Enable cross-border legal cooperation\n- Facilitate information sharing between countries\n- Support investigation and prosecution of money laundering cases\n\n3. Regulatory Compliance Requirements\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious Transaction Reporting\n- Due diligence procedures\n- Banks and financial institutions must adhere to international standards\n\n4. Enforcement Mechanisms\n- Coordinated investigations\n- Asset seizure and recovery\n- Extradition agreements\n- International criminal databases\n\n5. Sanctions and Penalties\n- Economic sanctions against non-compliant jurisdictions\n- Targeted financial restrictions\n- International blacklists for high-risk countries\n\n6. Information Exchange Platforms\n- Interpol financial crime networks\n- Egmont Group of Financial Intelligence Units\n- Facilitate real-time intelligence sharing\n\nThese intersections create a comprehensive global approach to preventing and prosecuting money laundering activities.",
